1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:25,650 --> 00:00:32,950
Welcome to God's Mills, the show that brings retribution to those who tortured our eyes and ears under the totalitarian regime.

3
00:00:52,430 --> 00:00:55,310
Some claim our show is controversial.

4
00:00:55,310 --> 00:01:02,770
They say we should leave the socialist stars alone, forget they once made our lives miserable, and let them go unpunished.

5
00:01:02,770 --> 00:01:04,670
That we should forgive.

6
00:01:05,830 --> 00:01:08,830
True, we've had some casualties along the way.

7
00:01:08,930 --> 00:01:12,690
Three heart attacks, two trips to the psych ward, and one group suicide.

8
00:01:13,320 --> 00:01:16,600
But you can't make an omelet without breaking eggs.

9
00:01:16,600 --> 00:01:20,980
And honestly, who misses the vocal ensemble of Lubomir Panek?

10
00:01:21,550 --> 00:01:25,250
But there are things that cannot be forgiven.

11
00:01:25,950 --> 00:01:27,050
Judge for yourselves.

12
00:01:27,850 --> 00:01:32,520
You'll soak into me like rain and I'll soak into you.

13
00:01:32,950 --> 00:01:35,650
You won't find such happiness.

14
00:01:36,750 --> 00:01:43,050
Even if you went to heaven, when you carry me away like a hurricane.

15
00:02:02,450 --> 00:02:05,810
The song "You'll Soak Into Me Like Rain."

16
00:02:05,810 --> 00:02:11,830
In 1988 alone, the totalitarian television broadcast it 326 times.

17
00:02:11,930 --> 00:02:17,190
And had it not been for the Velvet Revolution, it would have been featured at the Spartakiad during the exercise routine of older women with clubs.

18
00:02:19,450 --> 00:02:27,390
The song was performed by Tommy Patsy, which could be called a stage name, if only its bearer Tomas Pacovsky were an artist.

19
00:02:28,350 --> 00:02:32,150
Were you an artist, Mr. Pacovsky?

20
00:02:33,310 --> 00:02:35,670
Well, that's a complicated question.

21
00:02:35,910 --> 00:02:37,490
Try to simplify it.

22
00:02:39,250 --> 00:02:39,850
Well, I definitely enjoyed singing.

23
00:02:40,550 --> 00:02:45,520
I have a list of your achievements here.

24
00:02:45,520 --> 00:02:49,720
You were inducted into the Hall of Shame of Czech pop music in 1991.

25
00:02:49,720 --> 00:03:05,250
Jan Rejzek wrote that you should have drowned instead of Dean Reed, and in the poll "Who Should Go to Prison for Their Music" by Symphony magazine, you placed a nice fourth, right behind the stellar trio of Arnost Patek, Ales Ulm, and Marketa Muchova.

26
00:03:07,150 --> 00:03:09,850
You've been hiding from us for a long time, Tommy.

27
00:03:09,850 --> 00:03:15,570
And when we finally managed to film an official report about you and your delightful family,

28
00:03:15,900 --> 00:03:20,380
you sent your retarded brother after us, who destroyed all the footage.

29
00:03:23,150 --> 00:03:24,650
I was doing wheelies and then the cameraman got in my way.

30
00:03:28,190 --> 00:03:31,480
Jesus Christ, you ruined the footage.

31
00:03:31,600 --> 00:03:33,900
So nothing will come of all this?

32
00:03:35,650 --> 00:03:39,150
But maybe the footage could still be salvaged.

33
00:03:42,150 --> 00:03:43,750
It was an unfortunate accident.

34
00:03:44,150 --> 00:03:45,650
Sure, an accident.

35
00:03:46,050 --> 00:03:51,350
But when you planned this accident, you probably didn't realize you'd only draw attention to yourself.

36
00:03:52,750 --> 00:03:56,850
We at God's Mills grind slowly but surely.

37
00:03:57,450 --> 00:04:02,110
We therefore had to resort to the methods of investigative journalism.

38
00:04:02,110 --> 00:04:02,630
Nice.

39
00:04:03,750 --> 00:04:06,050
How are the new Black Agonies?

40
00:04:07,100 --> 00:04:07,620
Zdar?

41
00:04:09,150 --> 00:04:10,550
Good day, ma'am.

42
00:04:12,950 --> 00:04:13,950
That's a hunk, huh?

43
00:04:23,450 --> 00:04:24,450
Sick.

44
00:04:32,660 --> 00:04:33,980
I found out quite a lot.

45
00:04:33,980 --> 00:04:41,080
But to get Mr. Pacovsky here into our studio, we had to use an unconventional approach.

46
00:04:41,350 --> 00:04:44,250
Don't you want to wave to your daughter?

47
00:04:45,020 --> 00:04:46,860
I'm sure you'll see her again soon.

48
00:04:46,980 --> 00:04:48,880
If you behave.

49
00:04:49,950 --> 00:04:53,710
What hides behind the glossy facade of our mothers' idol?

50
00:04:53,950 --> 00:05:00,150
What is the true nature of the man hiding his real face behind the diminutive Tommy Patsy?

51
00:05:03,350 --> 00:05:23,150
Under his real name Tomas Pacovsky, he hides from the contempt his pop past brings him in a run-down music shop on the outskirts of Prague, which he runs together with his brother, an alcoholic with criminal tendencies, and his daughter Iva, who deals with family frustration by seeking out bizarre relationships.

52
00:05:23,150 --> 00:05:24,590
Please, stop it.

53
00:05:24,750 --> 00:05:26,790
Easy, Ivuska, this is between me and this gentleman.

54
00:05:27,010 --> 00:05:28,190
And me too.

55
00:05:28,290 --> 00:05:31,070
No stripper is going to lure our Ivuska away from home.

56
00:05:31,250 --> 00:05:32,390
Are you a stripper?

57
00:05:33,360 --> 00:05:33,840
I'm not.

58
00:05:34,140 --> 00:05:35,300
What kind of nonsense is this?

59
00:05:35,400 --> 00:05:35,740
But he is.

60
00:05:36,020 --> 00:05:37,340
He'd jump out of a cake for this one.

61
00:05:37,380 --> 00:05:40,060
I am not a stripper.

62
00:05:40,180 --> 00:05:40,680
Hold him.

63
00:05:46,750 --> 00:05:48,130
Load it up in here.

64
00:05:48,750 --> 00:05:49,950
You'll see.

65
00:06:03,760 --> 00:06:04,240
Help.

66
00:06:04,240 --> 00:06:10,440
How is that possible, when did you film this?

67
00:06:10,750 --> 00:06:12,550
I know where, but how?

68
00:06:12,850 --> 00:06:16,850
Hidden camera footage, standard procedure in problem cases.

69
00:06:17,550 --> 00:06:19,650
You smuggled a camera into the Badger?

70
00:06:20,010 --> 00:06:21,270
That's really dirty.

71
00:06:21,820 --> 00:06:23,400
It wasn't that adventurous.

72
00:06:23,440 --> 00:06:25,820
The manager was happy to cooperate.

73
00:06:32,750 --> 00:06:34,260
Restaurant "At the Badger."

74
00:06:34,650 --> 00:06:36,750
Seeing is believing.

75
00:06:42,250 --> 00:06:42,950
Simona.

76
00:06:43,850 --> 00:06:46,050
So you understand that we know a lot.

77
00:06:46,550 --> 00:06:49,850
But we're interested in your interpretation of the facts.

78
00:06:50,750 --> 00:06:53,340
You've undergone an interesting transformation, Tommy.

79
00:06:53,950 --> 00:06:59,350
From a singer who was everyone's laughingstock, you've turned into a failing businessman.

80
00:07:00,550 --> 00:07:02,650
Don't you see that as divine punishment?

81
00:07:02,930 --> 00:07:05,250
Well, I wouldn't see it so clearly.

82
00:07:05,250 --> 00:07:09,370
I don't know where you got information about our finances, but we actually are...

83
00:07:09,370 --> 00:07:10,350
From your accountant.

84
00:07:14,950 --> 00:07:18,950
Well, so to the first part of the question.

85
00:07:19,450 --> 00:07:19,850
I don't think I was everyone's laughingstock.

86
00:07:22,710 --> 00:07:25,710
You know, I had a lot of positive responses.

87
00:07:25,890 --> 00:07:30,170
And a lot of involuntary listeners whose lives you've marked forever.

88
00:07:31,150 --> 00:07:35,950
Well, but also a lot of willing female fans.

89
00:07:36,450 --> 00:07:45,030
We searched long for one who would still be willing to talk about it today without us having to pixelate her face and change her voice.

90
00:07:45,350 --> 00:07:49,850
But believe it or not, one such person really is still alive.

91
00:07:50,950 --> 00:07:52,050
And Tomas will really have a segment on the Czech Nightingale Awards?

92
00:07:55,590 --> 00:07:57,330
Yes, it will be a surprise for him.

93
00:07:57,530 --> 00:07:59,250
I always knew he'd come back one day.

94
00:08:00,510 --> 00:08:03,770
Fine, fine, but could we talk about what we agreed on?

95
00:08:04,650 --> 00:08:05,850
Of course, of course.

96
00:08:06,070 --> 00:08:06,550
So...

97
00:08:06,550 --> 00:08:09,690
I've prepared this for you.

98
00:08:11,350 --> 00:08:16,150
It's a record from Tomas's last major concert.

99
00:08:19,250 --> 00:08:20,050
Saturday, the 10th

100
00:08:20,550 --> 00:08:24,350
of February 1990, Bruntal.

101
00:08:26,050 --> 00:08:30,850
How easily people can condemn a top artist when he doesn't suit their purposes.

102
00:08:31,650 --> 00:08:35,860
Due to the post-revolution resentment, Tomy had to cancel his entire concert tour.

103
00:08:36,450 --> 00:08:41,350
Even the Prague House of Barricaders chose a textile sale over him.

104
00:08:42,050 --> 00:08:44,640
Only Bruntal remained loyal.

105
00:08:45,450 --> 00:08:51,250
There were seven of us in the pit below the stage, but our screaming made us sound like a crowd of thousands.

106
00:08:52,050 --> 00:08:58,690
When he sang for us for the last time, walk with me through the countryside, only roses grow there now.

107
00:08:59,350 --> 00:09:02,950
That I don't think of another, your love is to blame.

108
00:09:03,750 --> 00:09:10,550
The world seemed more bearable and tightening belts didn't seem so terrifying anymore.

109
00:09:12,150 --> 00:09:13,250
Thanks for everything, Tommy.

110
00:09:16,350 --> 00:09:20,650
Not only the swallows, you too will return one day.

111
00:09:21,750 --> 00:09:22,850
I'm sure of it.

112
00:09:25,950 --> 00:09:26,550
You remember.

113
00:09:26,550 --> 00:09:30,250
Do you want to come back, Tommy?

114
00:09:32,050 --> 00:09:35,080
Well, it's a different time now.

115
00:09:35,250 --> 00:09:37,050
Different, meaning worse.

116
00:09:37,550 --> 00:09:38,250
No, I said different.

117
00:09:39,360 --> 00:09:40,700
And you meant worse.

118
00:09:40,700 --> 00:09:45,550
If it weren't for the revolution, you could still be brainwashing the youth and getting paid in vouchers.

119
00:09:46,150 --> 00:09:47,650
I suffered too, you know.

120
00:09:47,650 --> 00:09:49,550
I had to go to a festival in Mongolia.

121
00:09:49,950 --> 00:09:51,150
Have you ever had kumis?

122
00:09:51,550 --> 00:09:53,450
Do you know how Alla Pugacheva kisses?

123
00:09:54,280 --> 00:09:55,260
Thankfully that's all over.

124
00:09:55,260 --> 00:09:57,150
I definitely don't miss it at all.

125
00:09:57,350 --> 00:09:58,120
Really?

126
00:09:58,450 --> 00:10:00,150
Are you sure?

127
00:10:01,450 --> 00:10:06,420
You'll soak into me like rain, and I'll soak into you.

128
00:10:10,450 --> 00:10:13,650
You won't find such happiness, even if you went to heaven.

129
00:10:15,550 --> 00:10:18,250
Please, could I speak with my daughter now?

130
00:10:18,450 --> 00:10:20,940
Unfortunately, she doesn't have her phone on her.

131
00:10:20,940 --> 00:10:22,320
Is that hers?

132
00:10:22,500 --> 00:10:23,020
Tough luck.

133
00:10:24,850 --> 00:10:26,150
Fine then.

134
00:10:26,450 --> 00:10:29,340
Sometimes I miss being more famous, yeah.

135
00:10:29,650 --> 00:10:31,840
People used to smile at me more back then too.

136
00:10:32,350 --> 00:10:35,040
It's true, in Hungary we always had everything.

137
00:10:35,550 --> 00:10:38,120
There were never problems with tangerines either.

138
00:10:38,250 --> 00:10:39,400
But don't get me wrong.

139
00:10:39,650 --> 00:10:42,340
I still had to stand in line for windshield wiper blades.

140
00:10:42,340 --> 00:10:43,060
Like everyone else.

141
00:10:45,350 --> 00:10:47,250
See, it's coming out of you now.

142
00:10:47,300 --> 00:10:49,060
Slowly but surely.

143
00:10:49,660 --> 00:10:52,140
Excuse me, could I get some water?

144
00:10:52,400 --> 00:10:52,960
No.

145
00:11:00,650 --> 00:11:04,130
Your brother, Mr. Pacovsky, works for you?

146
00:11:06,250 --> 00:11:07,450
Yes, I employ him.

147
00:11:07,950 --> 00:11:09,650
What salary do you pay him?

148
00:11:09,750 --> 00:11:10,250
I'm sorry?

149
00:11:11,750 --> 00:11:14,850
He's your employee, you surely pay him.

150
00:11:15,050 --> 00:11:15,650
How much?

151
00:11:17,150 --> 00:11:23,050
I don't really know off the top of my head, would you accept the answer in beers?

152
00:11:23,150 --> 00:11:25,670
Tomas Pacovsky, a.k.a. Tommy Patsy.

153
00:11:25,670 --> 00:11:31,410
This idol of Husak's children exploits his retarded alcoholic brother.

154
00:11:31,410 --> 00:11:33,730
No, no, please, that sounds terrible, don't say it like that.

155
00:11:34,090 --> 00:11:35,720
How should I say it?

156
00:11:38,840 --> 00:11:39,700
Hi, Simona.

157
00:11:39,880 --> 00:11:40,400
Hi.

158
00:11:40,950 --> 00:11:41,980
How come it's so empty?

159
00:11:41,980 --> 00:11:42,780
People don't come.

160
00:11:42,940 --> 00:11:43,700
I come all the time.

161
00:11:43,840 --> 00:11:45,740
You come, but you don't pay.

162
00:11:46,260 --> 00:11:46,860
How much?

163
00:11:47,150 --> 00:11:47,940
Fifteen hundred.

164
00:11:48,050 --> 00:11:50,650
And that's not counting the wrecked paneling in the bathroom.

165
00:11:51,850 --> 00:11:54,950
There was a poster of Heidi Janku glued on, couldn't be torn off.

166
00:11:55,050 --> 00:11:56,950
Now I put up a Rolling Stones one.

167
00:11:57,250 --> 00:11:58,250
You're a fan too?

168
00:11:58,250 --> 00:11:58,610
No.

169
00:11:58,750 --> 00:12:00,090
They had the biggest poster.

170
00:12:00,170 --> 00:12:01,330
It covered the whole hole.

171
00:12:04,950 --> 00:12:05,650
You're my bro.

172
00:12:06,250 --> 00:12:07,450
You're not getting paid.

173
00:12:08,130 --> 00:12:08,730
You're a jerk.

174
00:12:10,550 --> 00:12:13,650
Let's say I cover his expenses from his salary.

175
00:12:14,150 --> 00:12:17,550
Is he disabled, that he can't pay for himself?

176
00:12:18,250 --> 00:12:20,650
He's not disabled, how dare you?

177
00:12:27,650 --> 00:12:28,950
Look, I don't have a bed.

178
00:12:29,740 --> 00:12:31,260
I can reach the ceiling.

179
00:12:32,750 --> 00:12:33,440
Uncle, quiet.

180
00:12:33,440 --> 00:12:33,960
Ivuska.

181
00:12:34,960 --> 00:12:35,920
I went feral.

182
00:12:38,350 --> 00:12:41,090
Boy oh boy, that was some salmon.

183
00:12:41,550 --> 00:12:42,450
Who would've thought?

184
00:12:42,850 --> 00:12:43,550
Salmon.

185
00:12:44,450 --> 00:12:47,750
It looks like a cow with antlers but it tastes like fish.

186
00:12:50,950 --> 00:12:55,580
Well sometimes he behaves a bit... a little eccentrically.

187
00:12:55,950 --> 00:12:58,050
How eccentrically?

188
00:13:02,750 --> 00:13:06,950
That's weird, we already fixed that there.

189
00:13:07,600 --> 00:13:08,220
Ozzak.

190
00:13:11,350 --> 00:13:12,410
You didn't leave any there?

191
00:13:12,750 --> 00:13:14,050
Don't worry, Daddy.

192
00:13:14,330 --> 00:13:15,850
What's that supposed to mean?

193
00:13:15,970 --> 00:13:17,470
No more traffic accidents.

194
00:13:17,950 --> 00:13:21,130
You have to put those signs back immediately.

195
00:13:21,250 --> 00:13:26,490
The locations of the stolen signs are guarded by police in case the criminals return to the scene.

196
00:13:26,490 --> 00:13:27,450
Who has an alarm clock?

197
00:13:28,250 --> 00:13:33,350
Well, he just doesn't behave entirely normally.

198
00:13:33,650 --> 00:13:37,610
So an uninformed person might sometimes think he's a bit out of it.

199
00:13:37,950 --> 00:13:43,200
But everything he does or says has its own logic.

200
00:13:43,550 --> 00:13:45,250
You don't forget how to play drums.

201
00:13:45,450 --> 00:13:46,490
It's like riding a bike.

202
00:13:46,490 --> 00:13:46,890
Yeah.

203
00:13:46,890 --> 00:13:50,750
And do you remember how it went when you tried to ride a bike again two years ago?

204
00:13:50,750 --> 00:13:51,330
What about it?

205
00:13:52,250 --> 00:13:53,750
I dodged the dachshund.

206
00:13:53,750 --> 00:13:55,190
Yeah, but not its owner.

207
00:13:55,350 --> 00:13:56,270
She managed to jump out of the way.

208
00:13:56,390 --> 00:13:57,750
Under the wheels of an oncoming car?

209
00:13:57,850 --> 00:13:58,990
That car braked.

210
00:13:59,550 --> 00:14:01,850
Yeah, but at that moment three more crashed into it.

211
00:14:01,850 --> 00:14:02,990
So what, everyone survived.

212
00:14:03,230 --> 00:14:05,250
Even the cop said nothing really happened.

213
00:14:05,410 --> 00:14:06,610
Yeah, until you ran over his foot.

214
00:14:08,950 --> 00:14:10,270
See, two years and you still remember it.

215
00:14:10,550 --> 00:14:12,050
And what's your point?

216
00:14:13,550 --> 00:14:15,350
That you don't forget how to ride a bike.

217
00:14:17,150 --> 00:14:19,150
You've made that clear.

218
00:14:19,950 --> 00:14:23,150
But tell me, where do you pay for him?

219
00:14:23,290 --> 00:14:23,970
Where?

220
00:14:24,030 --> 00:14:24,870
At a friend's.

221
00:14:25,010 --> 00:14:26,510
Well, a former friend's.

222
00:14:26,530 --> 00:14:27,290
At a restaurant.

223
00:14:27,670 --> 00:14:29,170
Does she give you a commission?

224
00:14:29,350 --> 00:14:30,950
That's nonsense.

225
00:14:31,010 --> 00:14:33,550
I simply pay whatever my brother drinks.

226
00:14:33,730 --> 00:14:35,710
Often exceeding his monthly income.

227
00:14:35,830 --> 00:14:39,690
So you're actually enabling alcoholism in this poor man.

228
00:14:41,050 --> 00:14:42,850
Ozzak is not an alcoholic.

229
00:14:43,110 --> 00:14:43,790
Beer.

230
00:14:43,790 --> 00:14:44,350
Beersy.

231
00:14:45,450 --> 00:14:48,210
Little beer, I can't believe I went so long without those words.

232
00:14:48,610 --> 00:14:50,510
Marcelka, I need to talk to you.

233
00:14:51,570 --> 00:14:55,390
Ozzak talked to me all morning, but he kept saying practically the same thing.

234
00:14:55,710 --> 00:15:00,530
Twelve-degree, lager, dark, yeast, those words just caress the tongue, bro.

235
00:15:01,510 --> 00:15:02,750
Marcelka, I'm worried.

236
00:15:02,870 --> 00:15:04,650
I feel like he's overdoing it with work.

237
00:15:04,830 --> 00:15:06,230
It's nice that he's trying.

238
00:15:06,530 --> 00:15:09,450
Barley malts, hop products, lactic acid.

239
00:15:09,510 --> 00:15:12,890
Ozzak, you know how I once promised I'd never let you leave work early.

240
00:15:13,030 --> 00:15:13,770
Well, today-

241
00:15:14,810 --> 00:15:15,410
Really?

242
00:15:15,670 --> 00:15:16,270
Thanks.

243
00:15:18,350 --> 00:15:21,510
Ozzak and alcoholic, that's an exaggeration.

244
00:15:21,650 --> 00:15:24,050
He simply has a good relationship with beer.

245
00:15:24,750 --> 00:15:25,650
Really?

246
00:15:26,550 --> 00:15:29,650
So, beef in cream sauce, a small beer, Ozzak, thirteen hundred.

247
00:15:32,450 --> 00:15:34,950
But don't you think Ozzak's consumption is increasing?

248
00:15:35,550 --> 00:15:36,530
What do you mean?

249
00:15:36,650 --> 00:15:37,850
I just have a feeling.

250
00:15:38,050 --> 00:15:39,850
Wait, that could be a problem.

251
00:15:40,250 --> 00:15:43,870
The boss built his entire business plan on Ozzak's consumption.

252
00:15:43,870 --> 00:15:44,830
What's that you've got?

253
00:15:46,370 --> 00:15:46,830
An Ozo-meter.

254
00:15:47,410 --> 00:15:53,370
Well, from '99 on, based on this he could run a brewery.

255
00:15:54,150 --> 00:15:55,710
Sure, this is where Ivuska was born.

256
00:15:55,830 --> 00:15:58,230
Aha, and here you stopped singing in public.

257
00:15:58,230 --> 00:16:01,630
There's the '99 dip, but otherwise completely stable.

258
00:16:01,850 --> 00:16:03,650
The boss got a loan based on this.

259
00:16:03,750 --> 00:16:06,750
Your brother really isn't an alcoholic?

260
00:16:07,260 --> 00:16:07,720
He's not.

261
00:16:10,950 --> 00:16:12,150
Those were from driving school.

262
00:16:12,340 --> 00:16:13,960
Ozzak actually showed up there.

263
00:16:14,600 --> 00:16:15,380
Jesus Christ.

264
00:16:15,950 --> 00:16:18,220
And does anyone tell him you can't drink behind the wheel?

265
00:16:18,250 --> 00:16:20,450
He supposedly has a shot beforehand.

266
00:16:20,850 --> 00:16:25,250
If God's Mills finds out, they'll make a two-parter about us.

267
00:16:27,050 --> 00:16:32,050
To be perfectly honest, I've never really thought about it in detail.

268
00:16:33,550 --> 00:16:35,050
What a family.

269
00:16:35,550 --> 00:16:49,550
The cunning younger brother, who lived like a king under the communist regime, exploits and abuses his delayed, antisocial sibling, whom he deliberately turned into an alcoholic.

270
00:16:50,250 --> 00:16:53,150
And here we have modern-day slavery.

271
00:16:53,800 --> 00:16:55,820
Man, you're a real piece of work.

272
00:16:55,820 --> 00:16:59,750
I'm starting to regret we didn't plan a two-parter for you.

273
00:17:07,180 --> 00:17:09,040
Well, I'll tell you something, Mr. Zak.

274
00:17:09,040 --> 00:17:11,540
Your show is real filth.

275
00:17:11,750 --> 00:17:14,930
It's your filth, you should keep your house in order.

276
00:17:14,930 --> 00:17:16,030
And what about your methods?

277
00:17:16,030 --> 00:17:19,050
The viewers might be interested in your methods.

278
00:17:19,250 --> 00:17:21,550
You kidnapped my daughter and won't tell me where she is.

279
00:17:21,950 --> 00:17:25,350
I demand that you tell me what's going on with my daughter.

280
00:17:25,650 --> 00:17:28,590
I can tell you who's with your daughter.

281
00:17:28,590 --> 00:17:29,150
Who?

282
00:17:30,050 --> 00:17:31,350
Vasil and Abdul, my colleagues.

283
00:17:31,650 --> 00:17:38,520
Well actually, only Vasil is my colleague, he and Abdul know each other from Crimea.

284
00:17:38,950 --> 00:17:43,320
But don't worry, Vasil has always managed to handle Abdul so far.

285
00:17:44,150 --> 00:17:47,550
You're all Vasils and Abduls from Crimea?

286
00:17:48,350 --> 00:17:51,480
Don't take it so hard, your time is almost up.

287
00:17:51,850 --> 00:17:54,450
I actually have just one last question for you.

288
00:17:54,950 --> 00:17:56,850
Who is this?

289
00:17:58,150 --> 00:18:00,150
That's a kid from the neighborhood.

290
00:18:00,260 --> 00:18:00,760
Lexa.

291
00:18:01,850 --> 00:18:05,850
Your family has a special relationship with him, don't you?

292
00:18:08,650 --> 00:18:10,050
Grandma, come visit again sometime.

293
00:18:10,220 --> 00:18:11,240
No, dammit!

294
00:18:11,360 --> 00:18:12,580
What kind of a slip is that?

295
00:18:13,150 --> 00:18:14,960
No, it's not a slip, those are gloves.

296
00:18:14,960 --> 00:18:15,460
Lexa.

297
00:18:15,950 --> 00:18:19,350
Sorry, Mr. Pacovsky, Mom probably stopped shaving her legs.

298
00:18:20,880 --> 00:18:22,120
That's a hunk, huh?

299
00:18:22,440 --> 00:18:23,980
They opened a new stand across the street.

300
00:18:29,150 --> 00:18:34,850
But watch out for me.

301
00:18:35,550 --> 00:18:37,050
Well, he's at our place quite often.

302
00:18:37,550 --> 00:18:38,260
Often?

303
00:18:39,050 --> 00:18:41,380
That's a rather mild word, don't you think?

304
00:18:41,750 --> 00:18:43,100
He's the son of my friend.

305
00:18:43,100 --> 00:18:45,020
Well, former friend.

306
00:18:45,400 --> 00:18:46,200
Friend.

307
00:18:46,750 --> 00:18:47,950
I see.

308
00:18:48,150 --> 00:18:52,750
The aim of this show is to reveal who those people really were, the ones who brainwashed you with their whiny little songs.

309
00:18:56,090 --> 00:18:56,890
How...

310
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:01,280
All you need is a few friends and if we stay true to ourselves, we'll handle everything on our own.

311
00:19:01,280 --> 00:19:06,460
Especially if we're not mean and we're children of paradise, the girls from your kindergarten will remain the best.

312
00:19:06,760 --> 00:19:10,920
What was the name of the song on the B-side of your famous single?

313
00:19:12,150 --> 00:19:13,420
The Truth That Hurts.

314
00:19:13,850 --> 00:19:15,620
The lyrics were loosely based on Villon.

315
00:19:16,450 --> 00:19:17,550
That fits.

316
00:19:20,750 --> 00:19:23,340
I've already got plenty of catches under my belt.

317
00:19:23,750 --> 00:19:26,050
Thanks to discipline and self-denial.

318
00:19:26,550 --> 00:19:35,550
How else would the public have learned that Karel Gott's real name is Ludek Bina, had I not spent two weeks in his office disguised as a lamp.

319
00:19:35,910 --> 00:19:40,350
Weeks of surveillance around Tommy Patsy's family also paid off.

320
00:19:40,790 --> 00:19:44,610
Although the real bombshell had to be uncovered in Celadna.

321
00:19:44,730 --> 00:19:49,110
Where Mr. Pacovsky went to a trade fair for alcoholic supplies.

322
00:19:49,170 --> 00:19:52,830
Which our source, whom we thank, tipped us off about once again.

323
00:20:01,950 --> 00:20:04,150
The home of a true drinker.

324
00:20:07,550 --> 00:20:15,350
Our source, however, didn't expect that he himself would become the protagonist of the scandal our show is about to launch.

325
00:20:16,050 --> 00:20:25,850
The fake hotel renovation, where our target checked in without suspecting that a camera was hidden behind every cement mixer, paid off.

326
00:20:35,440 --> 00:20:36,840
So rooms, rooms, right?

327
00:20:36,860 --> 00:20:42,720
Easy for you to say rooms, but I've only got one room ready for you, 'cause we're kind of in the middle of renovations, right?

328
00:20:45,050 --> 00:20:48,450
But looking at you two, it probably won't bother you anyway, will it?

329
00:20:49,560 --> 00:20:50,200
Just a moment.

330
00:20:50,640 --> 00:20:53,240
I'm requesting my room that I reserved.

331
00:20:53,360 --> 00:20:56,020
I have a right to it and I'm not leaving until I get the keys.

332
00:20:56,850 --> 00:20:57,730
Well come on then.

333
00:20:57,730 --> 00:21:00,650
So the gentleman's a bit nervous, isn't he?

334
00:21:01,290 --> 00:21:03,670
Fine then, we'll do two, as you wish.

335
00:21:03,990 --> 00:21:04,310
There.

336
00:21:05,520 --> 00:21:06,360
Happy?

337
00:21:08,050 --> 00:21:10,350
Enjoy your stay.

338
00:21:10,740 --> 00:21:14,540
At this point I must thank my acting coach.

339
00:21:14,720 --> 00:21:17,540
It wasn't easy for me to be so slimy.

340
00:21:19,550 --> 00:21:24,160
Now we'll show you the dark family secret of Tomas Pacovsky.

341
00:21:24,750 --> 00:21:27,450
About which we still don't know enough.

342
00:21:27,720 --> 00:21:28,840
Where are we?

343
00:21:31,250 --> 00:21:32,350
And where are the kids?

344
00:21:32,950 --> 00:21:34,620
The kids are at home with Ozzak.

345
00:21:34,950 --> 00:21:36,220
My brother.

346
00:21:36,250 --> 00:21:38,860
Well then I'm not worried, if they're with your brother.

347
00:21:39,150 --> 00:21:40,150
I am though.

348
00:21:40,930 --> 00:21:41,450
Yeah.

349
00:21:42,750 --> 00:21:46,050
We probably shouldn't have left them alone with Ozzak, right Tomas?

350
00:21:47,650 --> 00:21:49,950
But they'll manage, the kids are resourceful.

351
00:21:50,550 --> 00:21:52,300
Tell me what's going to happen with us instead.

352
00:21:52,650 --> 00:21:54,080
Are you going to leave me again?

353
00:21:54,550 --> 00:21:56,050
What do you mean, what's going to happen with us?

354
00:21:56,650 --> 00:21:58,610
You're my husband, Libor.

355
00:21:58,950 --> 00:22:00,750
Don't you forget that.

356
00:22:02,250 --> 00:22:04,050
I'm not Libor.

357
00:22:09,950 --> 00:22:11,250
You don't know anything.

358
00:22:12,050 --> 00:22:14,350
But those kids are yours, Tomas.

359
00:22:17,060 --> 00:22:18,400
And there it is.

360
00:22:18,400 --> 00:22:24,880
Nice-guy Tommy Patsy denies his own son and lets him live in squalor.

361
00:22:25,350 --> 00:22:26,760
That's not true at all.

362
00:22:27,050 --> 00:22:29,660
When Simona is drunk, she confuses everyone with Libor.

363
00:22:29,660 --> 00:22:30,820
Why are you telling me this?

364
00:22:30,820 --> 00:22:36,620
So that viewers don't think I have children I don't take care of.

365
00:22:36,620 --> 00:22:37,520
And do you?

366
00:22:38,250 --> 00:22:42,850
No, I don't, I don't, I don't.

367
00:22:43,450 --> 00:22:45,810
Then you went through all that trouble for nothing.

368
00:22:46,360 --> 00:22:48,580
We'll cut out your "no" anyway.

369
00:22:50,050 --> 00:22:59,050
So, Mr. Pacovsky, the final question is, what kind of person are you really?

370
00:23:05,880 --> 00:23:06,440
Water!

371
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:08,120
Weigh the water!

372
00:23:08,780 --> 00:23:11,160
I think this speaks for itself.

373
00:23:12,750 --> 00:23:13,650
Please stop, stop!

374
00:23:16,400 --> 00:23:18,200
What is it, what are you doing?

375
00:23:18,420 --> 00:23:18,840
Where were you?

376
00:23:18,960 --> 00:23:20,020
What did they do to you?

377
00:23:20,450 --> 00:23:24,130
Nothing, they showed me where they film the show and where Borhy has her dressing room.

378
00:23:24,130 --> 00:23:25,110
Did you see she's a brunette?

379
00:23:25,330 --> 00:23:26,930
She has a lot of blonde wigs there.

380
00:23:27,170 --> 00:23:28,270
And those two guys?

381
00:23:29,250 --> 00:23:30,750
That's Vasil and Abdul.

382
00:23:30,750 --> 00:23:31,550
Producers.

383
00:23:33,610 --> 00:23:34,210
Hello.

384
00:23:34,510 --> 00:23:35,090
Hello.

385
00:23:36,350 --> 00:23:37,720
Hey, Vasil has a cottage in Crimea.

386
00:23:37,720 --> 00:23:39,060
He says I could go there in the summer.

387
00:23:39,240 --> 00:23:39,720
Please.

388
00:23:56,350 --> 00:23:58,850
This is how God's mills grind.

389
00:23:59,250 --> 00:24:02,650
Perhaps slowly, but relentlessly.

390
00:24:03,450 --> 00:24:04,850
See you next time.

391
00:24:07,050 --> 00:24:08,650
And you came up with this show?

392
00:24:09,950 --> 00:24:15,150
Yes, Mr. Director, but I must say that I'm obviously not working on it alone, that...

393
00:24:15,150 --> 00:24:16,670
What are the ratings?

394
00:24:25,550 --> 00:24:27,330
Who'd be interested in kicking dead bodies anyway?

395
00:24:27,330 --> 00:24:27,730
Exactly.

396
00:24:30,250 --> 00:24:31,950
But your contract is expiring soon, isn't it?

397
00:24:33,350 --> 00:24:36,970
Yes, Mr. Director, it is, but I've...

398
00:24:38,750 --> 00:24:42,090
Pisek is so adorably cute that...

399
00:24:43,650 --> 00:24:49,050
Can you tell me why we don't employ people who can come up with shows at least as successful as Emergency Room?

400
00:24:49,250 --> 00:24:50,450
I absolutely don't understand.

401
00:24:51,350 --> 00:24:52,850
By the way, have you come up with anything yet?

402
00:24:59,450 --> 00:25:00,530
Come on, Baron, let's go.

403
00:25:04,850 --> 00:25:06,250
Oh well, my little doggy.

404
00:25:15,750 --> 00:25:16,650
Baron, sit.

405
00:25:16,950 --> 00:25:20,250
Baron, Baron, Baron, lie down.

406
00:25:21,750 --> 00:25:25,150
Okay, let's do object recognition, Baron, yes?

407
00:25:25,850 --> 00:25:27,450
Pick the chicken.

408
00:25:27,850 --> 00:25:28,330
Now?

409
00:25:30,750 --> 00:25:31,450
Baron, which one is the chicken?

410
00:25:33,050 --> 00:25:34,750
That's not a chicken.

411
00:25:35,150 --> 00:25:36,750
This isn't going to work, come on.

412
00:25:37,050 --> 00:25:39,650
What did you say it should be called?

413
00:25:40,150 --> 00:25:42,650
The Funny Tricks of Baron the Dog.

414
00:25:44,350 --> 00:25:46,050
They'd have to approve it for us, right?

415
00:25:46,450 --> 00:25:53,450
I can't get anything out of this dog, he's terribly fixated on round objects.

416
00:25:54,550 --> 00:25:56,750
And he's in a trance.

417
00:25:57,350 --> 00:25:58,550
What are you doing?

418
00:25:58,950 --> 00:26:02,950
Don't forget we have to return that mutt before someone figures out we borrowed him.

419
00:26:04,930 --> 00:26:05,330
Damn!
